response.\n\n**Decision**: **Integration** (mock the LLM and test runner to verify the loop terminates correctly and all results are included in the error).\n\n---\n\n## Behavior 5: The full loop — generate, test, refine, test again — produces a working implementation for a function that a single LLM call typically gets wrong.\n\nThis tests whether the iterative refinement actually improves code quality. A pure mock could never demonstrate this because mocking the LLM means I'm not testing whether the refinement strategy actually helps the model produce better code. The real value is in whether the feedback loop—running tests, analyzing failures, and prompting the LLM to fix them—leads to a passing solution. I need either a real LLM or a sophisticated mock that simulates realistic improvement patterns based on test feedback.\n\nReal LLM calls are essential here, along with actual test execution. The pipeline involves multiple sequential steps where each LLM call depends on the previous test results, and the outcome is non-deterministic across different runs. This is a Workflow-level test because it validates the full agent loop: generate → test → refine → test again, with real LLM calls driving the refinement.\n\n**Decision**: **Workflow** (real LLM calls in sequence, each informed by test results, validating the complete iterative improvement pipeline).\n\nFor signature matching, the core question is whether we're just comparing extracted signatures or actually validating that the LLM produces matching ones. If it's pure logic on mock data, Unit or Integration suffices. But testing real LLM output pushes toward Agentic. The minimum viable test is likely Integration—mocking the LLM while verifying the extraction and comparison logic works. Unit is possible if there's pure parsing logic to isolate. System only matters if type checking requires subprocess execution. Agentic covers testing that the real LLM generates matching signatures. Workflow doesn't apply since this is a single, isolated behavior.\n\nFor code execution and test passing, we can't verify this at the Unit level since we need actual code to run. Integration with a mocked test runner could work, but System is more realistic—actually executing the generated code and its tests to confirm they pass. Agentic validates that the real LLM produces code that passes. Workflow isn't needed for a single generation step.\n\nFor failure message incorporation, the challenge is whether we're just constructing a prompt with failures or actually generating them. If we mock the test runner to return failure messages and verify the prompt includes them, Integration works. System is needed if we actually run tests to capture real failures. The minimum depends on whether we're testing prompt construction logic (Integration) or the full cycle of generating failures and using them (System). is the minimum. So:\n- Unit: 0.1\n- Integration: 0.7 (test loop control and result collection)\n- System: 0.1 (if we want real test execution)\n- Agentic: 0.0 (don't need real LLM)\n- Workflow: 0.1 (if we want real LLM iterations)\n\nIf I mock both the LLM and test runner to consistently fail, I can verify the loop termination logic at Integration level—that's sufficient to catch the bug where the service doesn't stop after 3 attempts.\n\nFor the final behavior, Workflow is the minimum since we need the full end-to-end cycle to produce working code. I could allocate 0.2 to Agentic (real LLM reasoning) and 0.1 to System (mocked LLM with real tests) to ensure the complete loop actually generates functional output.\n\nLooking back at the definitions, multiple sequential LLM calls where each iteration depends on feedback from the previous one constitutes Workflow-level testing. A single LLM call with test-and-refine would be Agentic at 0.1, but the full iterative cycle requires Workflow at 0.9.\n\nThe core question is really about what minimum infrastructure catches actual failures in each behavior, not